{"/service/ndnp/okhi/batch_okhi_leflore_ver01/data/sn85042303/0023728446A/1908010501/1077.xml":{"full_text":"Ardmore, Sunday, January 5, 1908.\nTHE DAILY ARDMOREITE.\nPAQB THREE\nTHE\nKING\nDR. KING'S\nNEW DISCOVERY\nFOR COUGHS and COLDS.\nFOR WEAK, SORE LUNGS, ASTHMA.\nBRONCHITIS, HEMORRHAGES\nAND ALL\nTHROAT and LUNG\nDISEASES.\nPREVENTS PNEUMONIA\nI regard Dr. King's New Discovery as the grandest medicine of\nmodern times. One bottle completely cured me of a very bad\ncough, which was steadily growing worse under other treatments.\nEARL SHAM11URG, Codell, Kas.\nPRICE OOo AND Sl.00\n3 SOLD AND GUARANTEED BY C\nARDMORE TRANSFER COMPANY\nPhone 74 TOM CARTER ,Prop.\nEUGENE COOK, Manager\nWo offer to the peoplo tho best transfer service in the city.\nOur hacks urc new. our drivers aro honest,\nsober and courteous\nhliilt line in Coooctlios.\nIt's never too Kite to reciprocate with some nice\npresent in Silverware, China, Rings, Pin or\ndiamonds. We arc still in position to save you money\nBUL ARD SON\nMis Hinds lino charge of training idiool for\nnurses, ltueive ujUi mt'dieal atid .urgieal pa\ntien's Thoroughly murium in every particular.\nSp.'cial operating room. Good sirvic', terms\nreasonable. The medical profession solicit d.\nDRS. IIAUDY, VO.V KELLKIl HENRY;\nArduiore, Okla.\nHas Taken Wings\nThe financial panic\nflown. We are now ready with a magnificent\nline of John Deere Plows and Cultivators,\nMitchell and New Molinc Wagons, Barucdg\nWire, Corrugated Iron in all lengths and we 2\nwill sell for cash or on time. See us for any\nthing in the hardware and implement line.\nBivens, Corhn Frensley\nShelf and Heavy Hardware, Stoves and Buggies\nFor the largest and best selected line of Christmas Booklets,\nCurds, Tags, Stickers, etc. seo\nHoffman Drag Conpany, Phone 651.\nor\nCURES\nPhone 74\nTails Answrrrd Promptly al all Honrs\nhas taken \"wings and\nTHEY FIGHT IN CHURCH\nCOUNT DONI DE CASTELLANE\nAND PRINCE HELIC DE\nSAGAN MIX.\nParis, Jnn. 4, Count Ilonl da Cas\ntelnuo, from whom Ills wife, who\nwas Miss Anna Cioiilil of Now York,\nwas recently divorced, and Prince\nHello tie Sagan, who on several\noccasions was reiwted to bo en.\ngaged to Mme. 'Could, had a person\nal encounter today at the Church of\nSt. l'lcrro do Challlot, whllo n ser\nvlco to tho memory of Ixuly Stanley\nKrrltigton, a relative of both men,\nwho died latidy In Hngtaud was In\nprogress. Itcglnnlng lnsldo tho\nchurch, where Count ltonl says tho\nprince Insulted both him and the\nsacred eillflce, tho encounter was\nresumed at tho doorway, where Count\nIlonl, followed by his brother, Count\n.lean do Castellatie, overtook tho\nPrince. Count Ilonl spat In his couus.\nIll's face. Then canio tho clash of\ncanes, folowed by a rough-and-tumblo\nfight on tho pavement, which ended\nIn tho cutter, whero tho men wero\nfinally separated by a big butcher.\nCount Ilonl, at tho moment of In\ntervention, was holding down the\nwell-night Insensible Prince, while\nJean according to eye-witnesses was\nadministering to him a sovero klnck\nlug. When the ihiIIco arrived the butch\ner was holding tho two principals In\nUio -fight, who wero covered with\nmid. The prince was bleeding pro\nfusely from n wound In the right\ntemple, whero ho had been hit by\nCount Ilonl's heavy stick. With tho\nbutcher's hand on his collar, Hon!\nwas haranguing a crowd which had\ntathercd as to why ho had spat\nin tho Prince's face.\nThe ollce Invited tho threo men\nt go to station home, and this,\nafter some d'sputlng they agreed to\ndo. All threo of them, bespattered\nwith mud. nccompanted tho police\nand, followed by several thousand\nsM-ope, then mnrchi-d on to tho\nstation, whero they made \"explana\ntions.\" Doth Count Bonl and tho Prince\ngave Ihelr own version of tho quarrel\neach claiming that Uio other was\ntho aggressor, but the Prince alone\nlodged a complaint charging tho\nbrothers with assault.\n\"A process verbal\" having been\nwritten out, acordlns to tho French\ncode, the men signed It and wero\nthen released. Tho case now- will\ngo before tho ol'llco Prosecutor who\nwill ilecldo what, If any, steps shall\nbo taken.\n13 SHE TO WED?\nRumor that Ethel Roosevelt will\nWed Chat. Glover.\nHy Southwestern Proas.\nWashington. Jan. 2. Mlas Bthol\nHooBevolt, now the \"young lady of\ntho White House,\" will bo given a\nball tomorrow night by (her father\nand mother, and tho members of\nWashington's joung social sot aro\nwaiting tho function with tho great\nest of Impatience.\nAs a matter of fact, tho ball will\nbo Miss Ethels Informal doming out\nparty and will mark her dobut In\ntho fashionable society of tbo na\ntional capital. Damo rumor has tn\nken advantage of tho occasion to roll\nundor her tongue many Juicy morsels\nof gossip concerning tho president's\ndaughter and her alleged lovo af\nfairs, nnd many of tho old damo's\nI ntd n aro circulating storloa to tho\neffect that thero will bo another\nwedding In tho Whlto Houso before\nPresident Roosevelt leaves.\nCharles Glover, son of bank pres-\nIdent Glover, Is most often mention\ned as tho leading suitor for tho hand\nand heart of tho fair Jllss Ktliol, al\nthough, other wUo ones Insist that\nCaptain McCoy, ono of tho pros!\ndent's inllltnry aides, Is In tho lead\nIn tht3 contest of tho Locklnvars.\nTho latter Is said to bo n favorlto\nwith Mr. Itoosovelt, who would wcl\ncomo him ns a son-in-law.\nToday In History.\n10GC Kdward tho Confessor, Saxon\nking of England died: born 1001.\n1S.19 Catherine do Medici, cruel and\nIntriguing queen of Franco, died\n1779 Stephen Decatur, commodore\nV. 8, N., bom In Slnnopuxcnt, Md.j\nkilled In a duol at llladsenburg,\nMd 1S20. Zohulon Montgomery\nPike, soldier and explorer of tho\nKocky Mountains, born In Lamber\nton, X. J,: killed 1813.\nlSUl Kmnia Abbott, prima donna,\ndied In Salt i.ako City.\nISO:, Foes fraternized at Port Ar\nthur; Husslan ollicera pormltted to\nreturn homo on parole and tho men\nheld ns prisoners of war.\nHearing January 14th.\nArdmorolte Special.\nGuthrlo, Okla., Jan. 1 Tho hear\nIng of the railroads complaining\na.salnst tho freight rate reduction on\ncoal has been set for Jan. 14. be\nfore tho state corporation conimls-ston.\nNews Forecast for\nthe Coming Week\nTho United States congressmen will\nreassemble .Monday and tho senators\nand represelitatles, refreshed by n\nperiod of holiday eheer, will enlor\nHH)ii tho real work of the Mission\nwith renewed vim. It Is likely that the\nreoiHnllig of congress will be tnketi\nadvantage of by the friends nnd sup\nporter of Speaker Joseph Cannon\nto formerly announce his candidacy\nfor tho republican presidential nom\nination. Scores of congressmen fa\nvor Cannon nnd the launnhing of the\nboom will bo attended by considera\nble enhuslnsm. Practically all of tho\nmembers of the republican hou\nwho have not favorlto tons In their\nown states aro solidly back of tho\nspeaker.\nAn Important legislative matter\nwhich will probably come up In (-ingress\nnoxt week Is the Clayton re\nlut Itiii. declaring against a third\nterm. The lesolutlon will bo pushed\nIn both, houses and a majority of\nthe Cannon adherents will vote for\nIt, and the measure will revive the\nsolid support of the democrats, thero\nIs little doubt of Its lxissage. Pres\nident Iloojoevlt's recent declaration\nthat he would refuse n nomination\nlor a third term has not removed the\nnecessity for such n congressional\nresolution ns a guide for tho future,\ndeclares the supporters of tho meas\nure. Inharmonious relations In tho na\nvy department which caused tho re\nsignation of vear-Adnilral Wlllard\nII. llrouson from tho office of chief\nnf tho navy bureau of navigation,\nwill likely receive tho attention of\nboth houses the coming week. Tho re\nsignation of llrouson, following close\n3ii tho heels of Henry lleuterdahl's\nattack upon tho bureau system of\niiuv) department hns relieved tho\nstrllo existing In the conduct of tho\nnavy and tho need for a more har\nmonious administration. As a result\ncongress will undoubtedly give a\nthorough airing to tho cases which\ni'nvo operated to bring about condi\ntions that all tho officers of tho na\nvy aro themselves anxious to have\nremedied.\nTho demand for tho relief of tho\nfinancial situation has become wide\nspread and when tho congressmen\nmeet Monday they will bo present\ned with numerous petitions from\ncommercial bodies all over tho\ncountry, asking for a speedy con\nsideration of the subject.\nAdditional railroad legislation has\nalso been demanded by many Im\nportant organizations nnd several\nesolutlons on this subject will be\nplaced before tho solons when they\ngather on Monday. It Is' tho general\nsentiment of congressmen, however,\nthat the time Is not opportune for\npassage of bills of this character.\nThaw Trial Again.\nTh trial of Harry Kendall Thaw\nfor tho murder of Stamford White,\nIs set for Monday before Justice\nVictor J. Dowilng In tho original\nbrantih of tho supremo court In\nNew York City. It Is expected that\nthero will bo little delay and that\ntho work of selecting a Jury will bo\ncommenced almost Immediately and\nbe continued with day and night\nsessions, until completed. District\nAttorney Jcromo will ngaln conduct\ntho prosecution, nnd Thaw will bo\ndefended by Martin W. Littleton, as\nsisted by several other prominent\nattorneys. Insanity will bo tho plea\nof the defendant, according o tho\npresent plans of tho defense. Any\nattempt to send Thaw to 1 a mad\nhouse will bo fought by Thaw's at\ntorneys, who declaro that his In\nsanity waB only teniornry and In\nduced by tho recital of tho wrongs\nsuffered by his wife, Kvnlyu Nesblt\nThaw, at tho hands of Stanford\nWhlto. Mrs. Thnw will again bo tho\nprincipal witness for thu defense.\nStandard Oil Cases.\nTho hearing befoto Judge Frank\nlin Ferris In tho government's suit\nto dUsolvo tho Standard Oil compa\nny of New Jersey, tho 100,000,000\nparent concorn of tho \"oil trust,'\nwill bo resumed In Now York Mon\nday. A mass of testimony whttft\nhas been given In other suits against\ntho Standard Oil company will bo\nIntroduced. What Is known ns tho\n'Utile AltonT caso against tho\nStandard Oil company of Indiana, Is\nnlso set for trial Monday In tho\nUnited States district court at Chi\ncago. In this caso tho Standard Is\ncharged with tho acceptanco of re\nbates from tho Chicago Alton\nrailway from Whiting, lnd to St\nlyouls. Tho Indictments contain\ni34 counts nnd If tho company Is\nfound guilty In all probability It will\nbe suliJeUrd to a fine of $2,fiS0,-000.\nElkln's Law Test.\nAttorney General llonaparte will\nprobably make hli first appearance\nIn tho United States supreme court\nns tne government's chief law of\nficer on Monday, wlien the rebate\ncaso against tho Great Northern,\nunder which the railroad company\nIs under sentence to pay a fine of\n$1,000 Is to be argued. This Is the\ncase In which the company seeks to\ntest tho Klklns law, under which\ntho flno was Imposed, nnd the attor\nney for the defendant, urging that\nthe law was repealed by tho rail\nroad rate law passed by congress.\nThe supreme court hns also set for\nargument next week the caso Involv\ning whether tho land owned by the\nUniversity of tho South at Sewanee.\nTeiin., Is subject to taxation under\nthe laws of the state.\nTwo Cent Tare Law.\nAnother case Involving the power\nof tho federal courts to Interfere in\nthe execution of state railroad rate\nlaws mill be taken up by the United\nStates supremo court on Monday,\nwhen tho federal Judges for the dis\ntrict of Nebraska aro ordered to ap\npear and show cause why a writ\nof mandamus, asked for hy tho state\nolllclals of Nebraska to prevent Inter\nference iwlth tho enforcement of tho\ntwo cent faro law, should not Issue.\nReturn of Prosperity.\nIt Is ostlmnted that not Iras than\n100,000 men, who have been Idle for\nseveral weeks owing to tho shut\ndown of plants In the great Indus\ntrial centers of the country, will re\nturn to work. In the steel mills nnd\nfactories of tho Pittsburg district\nalone about 40,000 men will share lu\ntho returning irosiorlty. In Cleve\nland at least 10,000 men will re\nsumo work at their former occu\npations and hundreds of great fac\ntories and mills In other cities will\nbegin operations on Monday,\nAokl to Sail for Home.\nViscount Aokl, tho Japaneso am\nbassador, will sail from San Francis\nco for Japan on Tuesday on tho\nsteamer Manchuria. Ho will bo suc\nceeded at Washington by Hogoro Ta\nkahlru, tho present Japanese am\nbasador to Italy and former minister\nto tho United States. Tho ofllclal\nreason given for Viscount Aokl's re\ncall was that his superiors of tho\nJapanese foreign olllco desired to\npersonally discuss with Mm tho con\nditions In America affecting tho Inter\nests of tho Japaneso.\nPolitical Pow-wows.\nWilliam Jennings Ilryan will bo\nIndorsed ns tho democratic candidate\nfor tho presidency at tho stato con\nvention of the Now York Progressive\nDemocratic leaguo, to bo hold In\nCooper Union, Now York, on Tuesday.\nOn tho same dato tho Kings county\nrepublican committee will meet In\nIlrooklyn, when tho fight for nnd\nagainst tho Indorsement of Gover\nnor Hughes for tho presidency will\nbo brought to a climax.\nNew Battleship Ready.\nTho new battleship Idaho, first of\ntho threo new war vessels to bo\ncompleted, Is expected to bo ready\nfor sea duty next week, whllo tho\nMississippi and tho Now Hnmpshlro\nwill ho ready In tho spring. Tho Ida\nho will bo commanded by Captain S.\nW. It. DIehl, former Judge advocate\nof tho navy, who Is in lino for pro\nmotion to the rank of rear admiral.\nBrazil to Greet Fleet.\nAmerica's armada under Admiral\n(.vans Is duo to reach Hlo do Jnne\nrlo, llrazll, next aSturday, nnd will\nspend ten days at that port. Tho\nfleot will bo mot by a squadron of\nBrazilian vessels and escorted Into\ntho harbor of Hlo with great pomp\nand ceremony, Many fotes and celo-\nbratlons will bo held In tho Bra\nzilian capital during tho stay of tho\ntars.\nFight for Senatorshlp.\nWith tho meeting of tho Kentucky\nlegislature Tuesday, tho fight for\ntho Illuo Grass senatorial to?a will\nbo Inaugurated lu earnest, nltlim'sli n\nfinal voto will not ho taken for\ntwo weeks. Tho contest Is for a suc\ncessor to James H McCreary, whoso\nterm expires March 4, 1909. Tho reg\nular Democratic nominee Is ox-Governor\nJ. W. C. Ileckham, although\nho Ij being opiosed by many demo,\ncrata. Former Governor W. C. Ilrad\ntoy will bo tho republican caucus\nnominee.\nCotton Crop Reduction.\nDiscussion of a proposition to\nreduce tho cotton acreage throughout\nteh south this year will be tho prin\ncipal matter before the convention\nof the Farmers' lvducatlon.il and Co\noperative union, to opn In Memphis,\nTenn., on Tuesday. Another Import\nant convention to bo held In tho\nsouth next week will bo that of the\nNational 1-cnguo of Commission Mer\nchants, which opens In Savannah,\n(In., on Wednesday\nFairbanks and Roosevelt.\nVice President and Mrs. Fairbanks\nwill give their annual dinner In\nhonor of President nnd Mrs Hoose.\nvolt nt their Washington residence\non Tuesday night.\nFOR FIFTEEN CENT COTTON\nPRESIDENT WEST SAYS HOLD\nFOR THAT Pn ICE DELEGA\nTION TO MEMPHIS.\nArdr Ito Special.\nSlu.uiee. Okla.. Jan. I. It Is the\nopinion of President West, of the\nfarmers' union, that cotton will reach\nfifteen cents tier pound before the\nproducers of the south turn It\nloos According to President West\ncotton U being held all over tho rot-ton-raising\ncountry In warehouses.\n\"In Pottawatomie county alone\nthere are 1,000 bales store! In ware\nhouses and many of the farmers are\nholding their cotton in private stor\nages. \"Tho Oklahoma delegation to the\nnational convention at Memphis, flf\nty strong, will leave lu a special\ntrain fur the convention rlt, to\nmorrow. Tills nicotinic Is being hi-ld\nfor tho purpose of lu-ipltiui; enthu\nsiasm among the cotton producers\nand tirgo them to hold their ordiict\nfor fifteen cents per pound\" he said.\nCAN FORCE THE RAILROADS.\nTo Dultd Sidetracks to Private Ware\nhouses. Ardmorelto Special.\nGuthrie, Okla., Jan. I. In an opin\nion today tuado In reply to an In\nquiry from tho Mndlll Grain and Ele\nvator company, Assistant Attorney\nGeneral lleushnw declared that rali\nroad comiKinlea could be forced to\nbuild freight sidings to private .ware\nhouses, provided the expense of the\nsiding in construction is borne by\nthu private concern. Tho opinion also\nsays that if a siding has already\nbeen constructed for a concern doing\na simitar business that thu company\nmight ho forced to build ono to tho\nfirm discriminated against.\nREDUCE OIL RATES.\nCorporation Commission's Action to\nHelp Independent Producers.\nArdmorelto Special.\nGuthrie, Okla.. Jan. 4. A general\norder covering tho entire stato was\nformulated by tho stato corimratlon\ncommission nnd will be olllclally pub.\nMailed and promulgatctl, lowering\nruteu .tti thit rnfiutwirtntlnti tit .ill\nThis action hy tho commission Is\ncalcinated to noip tno Independent\nproducers and rentiers.\nThu exact amount of the reduction\nlms tint liitiMi 1epli!rxl iiimiii v.)t lmt\nIt will reach near CO ier cent, It\nis uiouglil.\nLOCAL COTTON RECEIPTS\nSHOW A LOSS WHEN COMPARED\nWITH THE CORRESPONDING\nPERIOD OF LAST YEAR.\nCotton receipts at tho local yards\nfor tho year nmount to 1C,5'J7 bales,\nalMiut 1.000 bales behind last year.\nI ho report ot tho compress for th.s\nseason .when compared with, la.il\nseason nnd thu season boforo last\nfor tho corrusiondliig period show\na deficit lu tho number of bales\npressed to bo 3,720 ns against last\nyear, and 722 us against tho season\nbefore last\nTho cotton men stato that In nil\nprobability tho receptts for tho sea\nsou 1907-08 will reach about thu\nsame figures as last something over\n22,000 bales. Up to Saturday morn\ning thu compress company has press\ned for oxK)rt this season 31,322\nbales nnd for tho corresponding per\nlod timing thu season of l'J0rt-07 tho\ncompress proiHcd and shipped to ex\nport points 38,012 bales, and for the\nseason proi'dlug 3&.091 bales.\nTho receipts ut tho yards for thu\npresent season uru al thu National,\ni;,877, compros3 C.OjO, and at the\nFanner's Union 'practically 3,070\nbales.\nTho receipts this season will bo\nlnrger than what was at first ox\npected, although thu crop Is general\nly short throughout this section of\nthu country and Texas. Tho season\nthis yenr will In all probability wind\nup earlier and ns soon as thu weather\npermits thu receipts of thu local mar\nket will bo larger man for tho past\ntwo or threo weeks. It Is expected\nthat thu season will tn nil probabil\nity closo by tho middle ot March.\nMoves to Ardmore.\nMrs. Ixjtila Nivocho sold her res\ntaurant to Mr. Itoper and departed\nyesturday for Ardmore, whero sh\"\nwill reside in the future. Her broth\ner, Sam Morltz, who has been abslst\ning lu conducting tho restaurant for\nsome time, has gono to Ardmore.\nMrs. Nivocho moves to Ardmoro to\nbo near her brothers and sisters. Shu\nhas numerous frlonds tn Davis who\nwish her success wherever she goofc\nHer Tcsldenco Is being occupied by\nJas. Salisbury and family. Davla\nNows.\nDeWltts Little Early Risers aro the\nbest pllts known. Sold by W. 11.\nFrame. d&w\nCOMPARE OUR SERVICE\nWITH OTHERS.\nPostal Telegraph Cable Co.\nN. Washington St. Tel. No. 31.\nI hp Lresrent nntp\ni uu v li'muiiL i iuiui in Linn cil\nhas boon re cen tly ref u rn lshel\niniwiihuiMu (tins in iuua; ttir uvo\naccommodations to tho traveling pub\ni\n41 1111 W U nUIILIL 11IU l'tl LI UIMKU I J\nhotel ban a ntco Hamuli room It\nconnection. All tbo rooms liavo out\nhi ii ii nxnoHiiri .inn nrn nn nmnim wit\nhot ninl cold bat lis and aro wi\nheated and tho ventilation ta perfect\nHatcH, $2.00 per day.\nI 1 L II I' IIUIIII II I\nm ni i vriiiiriui nr-\nUto ArrL lAN 5 NU C\nah\n.i ii\nUH.-l IU IIL'MUU ID Uilll a\nthis office and sign an appli\nt i i\nl.,iiiuii. i ins must DC uon\nhefore the meter will he put ii\nAk